<font color="#FF0000">Y WE ARE NOW EXPERIENCING PTSD</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jan  7 23:31:51 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
IF YOU THINK WE WHINE ABOUT PTSD READ THIS<br><br>
The poor family members of the survivors and also witnesses to the  Oklahoma city bombing are being treated for PTSD as they should be, Yet! if a Veteran ask for what he is ENTITLED, Treatment, he's scorned.  Not only that, He better know the ropes or they will not get the treatment they need.  To all you couch brave folks out there<br>
the system is set up to discourage Veterans from getting treatment, the Veterans administration is so complicated that very few service officers really understand the process.<br><br>
The following is a letter that I wrote on behalf of a friend who was seeking help from the Vet. Admin. He had been paying for his own Psychotherapy since 1984.  While I was in the process of writing this letter to verify that he was wounded, so that he could get the treatment he was Entitled too, he tried to commit suicide.  Well the VA got the message and put him in the hospital for 30 days all of his doctors said he had serious psychiatric problems. Yet after 19 days a social worker who worked at the hospital had him dismissed because if he stayed any longer he would have received 100 % disability for the month&gt; This is the kind of crap Vets have to deal with. <br><br>
Dear Senator McCain and Staff,<br>
My name is James MacCreight, I consider it a privilege to have the opportunity to make note about the excruciating circumstances pertaining to the duty that my fellow Marine the honorable (Name changed for this letter) Robert Stone experienced.  The eve of March Thirty First  is now upon us.  So many nightmarish nights ago on March 31, 1968 began a hellish experience that lasted into the early hours of the next morning April 1, 1968.  <br><br>
At the time Robert Stone and I were proud members of Alpha Company, First Battalion Fifth Marines.  (The most highly decorated company in the USMC) That pride was based on the fact that we fought for each other.  We were assigned to guard duty on the Troui River bridge just south of Phu Bai.  Upon assignment of this duty we were told that this bridge had not experienced any contact with the enemy in over two years, we were told that we had earned this duty/relaxation time due to the fact that we had just left Hue City where out of the 875 men in our outfit only 20 had not been killed or wounded in the three weeks of fighting. <br><br>
I was the company radioman A-6 when the Hue City fighting erupted.  I was familiar with Robert Stone because my MOS {Military occupation specialty} was 0331 &quot;Machine Gunner&quot; and I was periodically assigned to Robert's platoon from weapons platoon, before I became A-6 radioman.  <br>
One of my duties was to gather reports from each platoon of the killed in action and wounded in action,  I distinctly remember reporting that Robert Stone was wounded in action during the battle for Hue City.  I was surprised when Bill James who was wounded along with Robert told me at a reunion that Robert never received his Purple Heart due to some intentional bureaucratic oversight in the crush of casualties being reported from Hue City.  Something to the effect that no more field wounds would be honored in Hue City because they didn't want to claim all the casualties, it might scare the folks back home.  The topic sparked a conversation and it was mentioned  that Robert was wounded on two occasions and had several close calls including the time he was sitting on the ground when a mortar round landed between his legs, luckily it did not go off.  It is my understanding that along with Bill James there is a retired Sergeant Major who also witnessed the incident when Robert was wounded.  Contact is being attempted so that they  can make a statement.<br><br>
Unfortunately I can only testify to having seen Robert Stone's name on the wounded in action list, I was not an eyewitness to the incident.  However I am a witness to seeing Robert on the morning of April 1, 1968.  In order to give an accurate account as to the condition of Robert Stone that morning I feel I would be remiss in my duty if I did not describe in detail the weeks and months that proceeded that day.<br><br>
In order to completely apprehend what we experienced, I will attempt to give you some insight into the life of a grunt.  We constantly lived in the bush (the field) we were given 20-24 year old C-rations to sustain us through the most depleting experience anyone could imagine.  The days osculated between extremely hot, to wet and cold.  As we shivered through the nights hugging our weapons our only companions were fear and loneliness.  Fear is and incredible emotion and countless times we cursed ourselves for being so scared and bringing shame upon ourselves for not being more of a man, after all no real man could get this scared, so often. <br><br>
High command always demanded more production out of each and everyone of us.  We went out on patrol all day and when we returned frequently we were required to stand watch on bunker duty all night.  We were constantly reminded that we were surrounded by regiments of the NVA and that any given moment they would come down from the surrounding mountains and overrun us.  Politicians accused us of not keeping our weapons clean and that was the reason they were jamming when we were in a fire fight.  &quot;Our weapons were cleaner than we were&quot; imagine what we were feeling about this accusation. (Later the manufacture changed something on the bolt that was causing the problem)  Consider the political chaos here at home, it had a serious effect on our psyche.  We had poor morale and having to perform at a maximum level when your morale was so low created situations the average man could not even fathom.  One example of that happened quite frequently, the man in front of you points to a booby trap and says words of warning and you don't even try to move your foot off to the side if it's going to fall on it.  Due to so many casualties day in and day out, you just say to yourself let me just get it over with.  (The average soldier during WW2 served in combat an average of 40 days a year for four years.  The average soldier in Vietnam served 260 days in combat in one year)  <br><br>
Our outfit had been in constant battle since August 1967.  We were in Phu Loc when the Tet offensive started, we were rocketed day and night.   On a daily basis we made contact with the enemy and had to maneuver under Motor, Rocket, Machine Gun and Rifle Fire.  There were times we avoided the enemy because we did not have enough ammunition to sustain a serious fire fight.  <br><br>
Because the Marines attached to the CAP 23 compound were over-run and some of  them killed, our company was deployed to guard the encampment and keep the road open.   The camp was positioned at a bend in the road, this caused all vehicles to slow down in order to negotiate the turn .  The NVA were positioned on the mountain above us and every time a vehicle came down the road they fired a rocket, due to the slope of the terrain it missed the vehicle and hit us.  This went on all day.  In one of the surrounding villages we attacked and rescued the Vietnamese people who had survived the attack on their village by the NVA.  They were being held prisoner in their own church.  The people came running out screaming and crying stuffing their personal belongings into the pockets of our jungle fatigues simultaneously thanking us for rescuing them and pleading for us not to leave.  It was the first and only time during our whole tour that seemed as if what we were doing, made sense.  We were told the NVA  had moved into the next village.  Our company did an on line assault across a huge, wide open rice paddy (talk about scary) to also take that village back.  When we return a few hours later we found the people we had spoken with, assassinated, shot threw the head, one had a sign draped around his neck that said, &quot;you die if you talk to punk marines&quot; <br><br>
When we got to Hue City the situation had gotten so grave they started bringing Marines in from embassy duty in other countries, they were given 1 month credit for every 2 months they had spent in other countries.  We would get replacements that only had 20 - 30 days of time to do in the Nam, some with as little as 9 days to do and almost to the man they were killed, few lasted days and all of them were still wearing their state side utilities.  We felt the world crumbling all around us and we had to become animals in order to survive.  We felt we had to be cold to all those boots (new men) we could not allow ourselves to become attached to them in anyway for fear that we too would become vulnerable in some way. <br><br>
It has been estimated that there were between 3000-10000 men women and children were killed in Hue City.  Robert was there as we walked over those bodies having to smell the stench of dead human beings and if that wasn't objectionable enough we were ordered to gather them up in piles and sprinkle diesel fuel on them and to keep them burning we added car tires.  Piles and piles of dead Marines were in our face and a piece of ourselves went into ever bag we zipped up.  We could not help but think about the fact we just saw them only a few minutes ago or we just joked with them and now they can't even move as much as an eyelash.  Our thoughts and emotions went with them frustrated by the fact that we wanted his loved ones to know what a great guy he was and how proud they should be, if only they could have seen him shine and perform under the worst situations as we did.  Did they know the boy they sent died a man?<br><br>
Prior to going to Hue City we were in Phu Bai I can remember the lines at the latrine being so long it was heart breaking to get in line with our intestines in knots.  The battalion corpsman told us if there were not so many of us sick we would be hospitalized.  We had anemic dysentery for months.  We were down to the bone and we had to hump gear that weighed almost as much as we did.<br>
 <br>
 So when I think about March 31 and the 300 - 500 NVA that attacked and overran the 43 of us. I remember the way the night began with precision mortars raining down on us and North Vietnamese Soldiers on the roofs throwing satchel bombs into the buildings then teams of grenadiers tossing grenades into the windows and flares shooting into the dark night only to illuminate  the Zappers coming through the wire in a frenzy, bent on destroying us no matter what the cost to themselves.  The screams throughout the night, some of them coming from one of our closest friends Walter Jones, (Name changed for this letter)  pleading for someone to come and help him on the bridge where he finally succumbed to his wounds after unknowingly unnerving us all with his horrific cry's for help.  (Walter's inseparable friend Jimmy Smith (Name changed for this letter)  died later that day from the wounds he received trying to rescue Walter)  He was Robert's friend &amp; squad leader.  Intelligence said that during the night some of  the ARVN soldiers deserted their post and provided access into our camp for the NVA.  <br><br>
I want to take this opportunity to describe being in an explosion. <br><br>
Somehow your brain goes into an emergency response mode, everything becomes slow motion, you hear an inner voice coaching you too relax and not resist.  The only way to describe it is to imagine the wind going by you at such an incredible speed that your body begins to deteriorate and if  your lucky enough that it doesn't kill you, you have to instantly shake it off, because, &quot;there is no time out in combat&quot;.  Instantly you deal with your innate fears, your body is numb all over, so you take an accounting  of your body parts you may look down to see your hands, a slight felling of encouragement is felt inside when you realize there still attached, quickly you run them through your hair feeling for your ears and checking for any gaping wounds on your head.  You can feel your body quake as your hand bolts to your groin to see if your still a man, now your really encouraged, even before you check to see if your lower extremities are still there, you know you have enough body parts to make it back in the world. (back at home)  Now! you check for your legs and feet.  Think about what it was like as we tried to focus after having survived the explosions that tore at your body.  As if that's not enough,  THINK about the despair that we all felt waiting and waiting for help only to be emotionally crushed by the radio message You're On Your Own .  <br><br>
High command decided they could not risk sending reinforcements fearing that they would be ambushed.  No one thought they would make it through the night. In our minds years went by as we reflected on our families and loved ones,  wishing for the daylight to come knowing the NVA would disappear as if they were never even there.  Finally the light came and with it came the silence.  Peace was restored to nature as the reality of what happen set in, 15 Marines along with 12 ARVN were KIA and I believe everyone else was wounded. I've been told 169 dead NVA were in the wire and surrounding area.  To this day as I chat with my friends the harshly vivid memories come instantly to our minds.  I think the fact that sums it all up, is were just beginning to be able to speak about it 29 years later.  <br><br>
So with all this in mind I do testify that I James MacCreight was being assisted to a helicopter by our great corpsman Doc. Turley.  When we stopped to look at Robert Stone, he was devastated.  I tried to assure Bob that everything was going to be all right, his eyes never moved, I stood there and looked into them, he was a million miles away, he never even blinked when I ran my hand in front of his eyes.  I've seen many men with the stare of being in another time or place but, I never seen anyone as lost as Robert Stone I said to the Doc. that he'll be a basket case for the rest of his life.  Fortunately for all of us this is not the case.  It's absurd to know that he was back in the field in a matter of days.  When I speak to Bob on the phone I hear in his voice the pain of the past and the frustration of today, that even after all these years were still trying to sort out what happen to us. <br><br>
Even though he was given the Navy Commendation with V for Valor for his outstanding service while serving with Alpha Company, Robert like so many others has expressed feelings of guilt, wishing he could have done more.  I've encountered  many Vets with PTSD and I always tell them we're just perfect considering what happen to us.  It's all about cause and effect.  The real tragedy lies in the fact that we volunteered to serve our country, what we did not bargain for was having to deal with PTSD everyday for the rest of our lives.<br><br>
I hope this letter can assist you in understanding what happen to Robert Stone and that he be given the treatment and benefits he so honorably deserves.  I certify that the statements on this form are true and correct to the best of my knowledge and belief.<br><br>
Sincerely yours<br><br>
James MacCreight <br>
Four Purple Hearts<br><br>
&quot;Before I sign off I want you all to know.  It gives me great satisfaction to know that chances are that someday <br>
the people who come down on my fellow Vets for wanting to talk about there PTSD will most likely end up on an operating table with some kind of heart disease and when they are laying there wide awake and so incredbly scared I want them to remember this &quot;Welcome to Vietnam&quot; because that's the kind of fear we dealt with everyday for our whole tour.&quot;<br><br>
Compassion: Deep awareness of the suffering of another coupled with the wish to relieve it.<br><br>
  <br><br>
 <br>

